hildren","fullItemName":"Scenario: Delayed walking in children"},{"id":"f63a11de-e155-5afe-a226-402d885f4423","slug":"limp-in-children","fullItemName":"Scenario: Limp in children"},{"id":"da28c3e0-278d-5fce-8968-bdc734d3e305","slug":"out-toeing","fullItemName":"Scenario: Out-toeing"},{"id":"3130a07e-303c-5b73-838c-5d6307fdead8","slug":"tip-toe-walking","fullItemName":"Scenario: Tip toe walking"}]},{"id":"086fd10d-b722-534e-b18d-5a0a2d5792c9","fullItemName":"Supporting evidence","slug":"supporting-evidence","subChapters":[]},{"id":"bf424233-1954-55a8-98de-834693dbdd11","fullItemName":"How this topic was developed","slug":"how-this-topic-was-developed","subChapters":[{"id":"6728c56f-47a6-56f1-be0e-22c22275d9e9","slug":"search-strategy","fullItemName":"Search strategy"},{"id":"2d75ec25-86dd-542a-b968-a3f7e80d0210","slug":"stakeholder-engagement","fullItemName":"Stakeholder engagement"},{"id":"2514c9ed-51af-51be-8f7d-3a997605efe6","slug":"evidence-exclusion-criteria","fullItemName":"Evidence exclusion criteria"},{"id":"6bdf3ba0-4bec-595d-bb71-c68f7fcb7c9c","slug":"organizational-behavioural-financial-barriers","fullItemName":"Organizational, behavioural and financial barriers"},{"id":"20bd862c-7ca7-5a5b-8f5d-443cd0bea04c","slug":"declarations-of-interest","fullItemName":"Declarations of interest"}]},{"id":"b747cefd-4366-540b-87c3-72fdbb926a30","fullItemName":"References","slug":"references","subChapters":[]}]},"parentChapter":{"id":"8d402bd6-6ff7-597f-8744-fe50598828b1","slug":"management","fullItemName":"Management"},"subChapters":[{"id":"d14cabbc-d1aa-57bb-8925-a14f0adf12a8","slug":"flat-feet","fullItemName":"Flat feet","depth":3,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 3772faab-c579-4e5e-b7b3-aa0d00e620b6 --><h3>When should I consider referring a child with flat feet?</h3><!-- end field 3772faab-c579-4e5e-b7b3-aa0d00e620b6 -->","summary":null,"htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item a0f8413c-56fa-4060-a9db-aa0d00e620b6 --><!-- begin field 939de98e-fc4a-429e-a5c5-aa0d00e620b6 --><ul><li><strong>Management in the community (for example by a physiotherapist or podiatrist with paediatric expertise) is usually appropriate for a child with flat feet if <em>all </em>of the following are present:</strong><ul><li>The child is under 6 years of age, well, and there are no <a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/diagnosis/assessment-for-red-flags/\">red flag</a> features.</li><li>Flat feet are painless and flexible.<strong> </strong></li><li>There is no limp or interference with daily activities such as playing or walking.</li><li>There is no pain in legs or joints.<strong> </strong></li><li>Milestones are normal.<strong> </strong></li><li>No blisters or callosities are present.<strong> </strong></li></ul></li><li><strong>Consider referring children with flat feet for specialist assessment, using clinical judgement to determine the urgency, if <em>any</em> of the following are present:</strong><ul><li><a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/diagnosis/assessment-for-red-flags/\">Red flag</a> features.</li><li>Flexible and <em>painful</em> flat feet, or previously painless flat feet that become symptomatic. </li><li>Absent medial longitudinal arch when the child is on tiptoes or when big toes are extended.</li><li>Rigid flat feet (especially in adolescents — possible tarsal coalition). </li><li>Asymmetrical flat feet. </li><li>Tripping or frequent falls.<strong> </strong></li><li>Limp. </li><li>Functional limitation.</li><li>Fatigue of the foot muscles, signs of pressure such as calluses or blistering to the foot, or recurrent ankle sprains.</li><li>Marked hypermobility. </li><li>Morning stiffness, restriction of joint movement, joint swelling (of any joint, not just the foot/ankle), or abnormal joint examination.</li><li>Regression or delayed motor milestones.</li><li>Other features indicative of an underlying diagnosis, for example neurological (cerebral palsy), muscular (muscular dystrophy), syndromic (trisomy 21) or connective tissue (Marfan's and Ehlers-Danlos syndromes).</li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field 939de98e-fc4a-429e-a5c5-aa0d00e620b6 --><!-- end item a0f8413c-56fa-4060-a9db-aa0d00e620b6 -->","subChapters":[{"id":"256d6035-87b2-5b90-897e-3a5367a97141","slug":"basis-for-recommendation-ae3","fullItemName":"Basis for recommendation","depth":4,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 261a0a55-f8dd-4f27-905f-aa0d00e620b7 --><h4>Basis for recommendation</h4><!-- end field 261a0a55-f8dd-4f27-905f-aa0d00e620b7 -->","summary":null,"htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item ae3ff4ad-41b4-44a0-a97a-aa0d00e620b7 --><!-- begin field e8221670-d2a1-411f-936c-aa0d00e620b7 --><h4>Community management</h4><ul><li>The recommendation on when community management is usually appropriate is based on musculoskeletal triage guidance for children and young people [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">RightPath, 2017</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">RightPath, 2019</a>], a clinical practice guideline on paediatric flat foot [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Harris et al, 2004</a>], and expert opinion in review articles [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Dare and Dodwell, 2014</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Yeo et al, 2015</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Carr et al, 2016</a>].  <ul><li>There is evidence to suggest it is safe and appropriate for an asymptomatic child with flat feet to be managed with observation [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Yeo et al, 2015</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Carr et al, 2016</a>]. If there is no pain, management by operative or non-operative measures are not better than simply observing the child [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Carr et al, 2016</a>]. Most painless flexible flat feet do not require treatment and there is no evidence that orthotics change the natural history of arch development [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Dare and Dodwell, 2014</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Yeo et al, 2015</a>]. Rigid flat feet do not necessarily require treatment if they are asymptomatic [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Dare and Dodwell, 2014</a>].  </li></ul></li></ul><h4>Referral</h4><ul><li>The recommendation on when to consider referral is based on musculoskeletal triage guidance for children and young people [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">RightPath, 2017</a>], an explanation of the pGALS (paediatric Gait, Arms, Legs, and Spine) examination [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Foster, 2013</a>], a clinical practice guideline on paediatric flat foot [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Harris et al, 2004</a>], and expert opinion in review articles [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Yeo et al, 2015</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Carr et al, 2016</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Evans, 2017</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Rerucha et al, 2017</a>].  <ul><li>Experts suggest that physical therapy, bracing, or a surgical procedure (rarely indicated — for example Achilles tendon lengthening, osteotomies, joint fusion) may be beneficial for children with painful flexible flatfoot, and orthotics can provide relief of pain and prevent shoe deformation. For painful or functionally limiting rigid flat feet, orthotics, osteotomies, or fusions may be beneficial [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Dare and Dodwell, 2014</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Yeo et al, 2015</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Carr et al, 2016</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Rerucha et al, 2017</a>]. </li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field e8221670-d2a1-411f-936c-aa0d00e620b7 --><!-- end item ae3ff4ad-41b4-44a0-a97a-aa0d00e620b7 -->","subChapters":[]}]}]}}},"staticQueryHashes":["3666801979"]}